## How it works — Under the Hood

```
Angular App              Keycloak                   .NET API
    |                       |                           |
    |-- login (scope:       |                           |
    |   users:read,         |                           |
    |   users:write) ------>|                           |
    |                       |-- check user has roles    |
    |                       |-- grant scopes            |
    |<-- access token -------|                           |
    |    aud: angular-days-demo                         |
    |    resource_access.angular-days-demo.roles        |
    |                       |                           |
    |-- GET /api/users (Bearer token) ----------------->|
    |                       |                           |-- fetch JWKS from Keycloak
    |                       |<---- JWKS ----------------|
    |                       |                           |-- verify token signature
    |                       |                           |-- validate aud claim
    |                       |                           |-- extract resource_access roles
    |                       |                           |-- check "users:read" -> 200 OK
    |<-- 200 [users] -----------------------------------|
```

1. The Angular app requests `users:read` and `users:write` scopes during login.
2. Keycloak grants the scopes only if the user has the corresponding client roles, then adds them to `resource_access.angular-days-demo.roles` in the token.
3. The audience mapper adds `angular-days-demo` to the `aud` claim.
4. The API validates the token signature, checks `aud`, extracts the roles from `resource_access`, and maps them to .NET role claims.
5. The `[Authorize("users:read")]` attribute checks whether the role is present — if not, it returns `403 Forbidden`.

---

## Done!

Your API is now properly secured with Keycloak. Only authenticated users with the correct roles can access protected endpoints, the token is scoped to this specific API via the audience claim, and the Angular frontend requests only the permissions it actually needs.